<Base title="From physics model to production KPI service — Andrew Yang">
  <p><a href={`${base}/work/`}>← Case studies</a></p>
  <span class="tag">domain × backend</span>
  <h1>From physics model to production KPI service</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Yield-loss models and device-level KPIs are where domain knowledge meets
    backend engineering: every number a customer bills against starts as a
    formula and has to end as a service.
  </p>

  <h2>Context</h2>
  <p>
    When a solar plant is curtailed — told by the grid operator or a direct
    marketer to produce less — the energy it <em>didn't</em> produce is money,
    and someone has to compute it defensibly. Batteries add their own questions:
    how hard is a battery being cycled, and how available is it really?
  </p>

  <h2>Six models, one service</h2>
  <p>
    I built the yield-loss calculation service from specification to production:
    <strong>six loss models</strong> — simulation-based, linear-equation,
    reference-system, reference-component, flat-rate, and peak/simplified-peak —
    each a different trade-off between accuracy and the data a plant actually
    has. Choosing the model is the customer's call; making every model
    consistent, versioned, and explainable is the service's job.
  </p>

  <h2>Opening the device-level KPI line</h2>
  <p>
    The platform's KPIs had always been system-level. The first
    <strong>device-level KPI</strong> — Full-Cycle-Equivalent for batteries —
    required a new schema pattern for per-device daily values, and each KPI
    spans the full chain: OpenAPI spec → database schema → Kotlin service
    endpoint → calculation module in the import pipeline. Battery Availability
    followed the same pattern immediately, which is the point: the first one
    created the groove for every one after it.
  </p>

  <h2>Supporting cast</h2>
  <ul class="clean">
    <li>
      Monthly and yearly resolutions for the measurement-data API, computed by
      <strong>aggregation in the database</strong> rather than hauling raw
      series across the wire — the difference between a feature and a timeout.
    </li>
    <li>
      Spec-first throughout: every service boundary is an OpenAPI contract
      generating the Kotlin server, Kotlin client, and PHP client — the compiler
      enforces cross-repo compatibility before review does.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What I'd tell my past self</h2>
  <p>
    Domain formulas are the easy part; the engineering is in the boundaries —
    where a model's inputs come from, what happens when they're missing, and
    which resolution the database should own. Get the first schema pattern
    right, because every subsequent KPI will copy it, mistakes included.
  </p>
</Base>
